const summaries = { lastRace: "Monaco was the season's lowest-scoring race by a wide margin — the league average cratered to just 11 points as DNF penalties ravaged the field. Jane led all managers at 39, with Timo and Charlie both posting 36, while Kimi Antonelli was the standout individual driver with 55 points on the weekend. Jay took the sharpest hit at -37, both Lando Norris and Valtteri Bottas going negative simultaneously for the worst single-round score posted by anyone all season.", season: "Timo is running away with this league at 346 points — a 113-point cushion over second-place Margaret, built almost entirely on Kimi Antonelli's absurd 309-point individual haul. Margaret has locked in second with relentlessly consistent scoring from both her drivers, while Charlie sits last at just 16 total after a catastrophic Canada nearly ended his season before Monaco threw him a lifeline.", players: { "Alyssa": "Third place at 188 points, with Max Verstappen (144 pts) doing the heavy lifting and Sergio Perez (44) mostly along for the ride. Your 71-point Miami round was the season peak, but back-to-back weak finishes in Canada and Monaco (-3) show how tightly your ceiling is tied to Max actually delivering.", "Nora": "Fifth at 160 points, bouncing back hard from a -8 Australia opener — your Japan, Miami, and Canada stretch of 47, 54, and 37 was one of the most sustained hot streaks in the mid-table. Oscar Piastri (94) has stabilised after two early DNFs and Franco Colapinto (66) has been a handy second pick.", "Jay": "Ninth at 63 points, and the math is brutal: Lando Norris (78) is a legitimate top driver but Valtteri Bottas (-15 for the season) has burned you with DNF penalties in three separate races. Monaco's -37 is the single worst round score posted by any manager all season, and closing that gap without fixing the Bottas problem looks nearly impossible.", "Margaret": "Second at 233 points with the most consistent lineup in the league — George Russell (157) and Esteban Ocon (76) have both posted positive individual scores in every single race this season. You're 113 back of Timo but comfortably clear of the chasing pack; just keep the floor high and wait for the leader to blink.", "Cecelia": "Fourth at 171 points, and this is almost entirely a Charles Leclerc (152 pts) story — Gabriel Bortoleto (19) has been a minimal presence all season. You were admirably steady across five rounds, but Leclerc's Monaco DNF snapped the momentum right when you needed it; Bortoleto needs to start chipping in more than token points.", "Timo": "Runaway leader at 346 points, and it's really a one-driver show — Kimi Antonelli's 309-point individual total is the highest driver tally in the league, combining elite qualifying scores, multiple fastest laps, Driver of the Day awards, and zero DNFs all season. Oliver Bearman (37) has taken two DNF penalties of his own but it barely registers when Antonelli is this dominant.", "Mary Beth": "Sixth at 135 points, torn between Lewis Hamilton's quiet reliability (181 pts) and Lance Stroll's total chaos (-46 pts, four DNF penalties across six races). Hamilton has been one of the season's steadiest performers; Stroll is the most destructive individual liability in the entire league, and that contrast is your whole story.", "Jane": "Seventh at 106 points, with Liam Lawson (77) providing the dependable scoring and Isack Hadjar (29) swinging between solid and catastrophic — strong in China and Monaco but dragged by DNF penalties in Australia and Miami. Your 39-point Monaco finish is your best single round all season and there's some real momentum building.", "David": "Eighth at 89 points, with Carlos Sainz (68) and Alexander Albon (21) forming about as reliably mid-pack a pairing as you'll find in this league. Your ceiling was 39 in Miami, you've posted just 3 points in two separate rounds, and without a higher-upside driver it's hard to see a route into the top half.", "Charlie": "Last place at 16 points, with Fernando Alonso (-8) and Arvid Lindblad (24) both struggling to string anything together consistently. Canada's -42 was a near-total wipeout, but the 36-point Monaco bounce is genuine — you need sustained versions of that and fast if this season is going to be anything other than a write-off.", "Sarah": "Tenth at 37 points, and Nico Hulkenberg (-28 for the season, DNF penalties in three separate races) is the deadweight dragging down Pierre Gasly's otherwise serviceable work (65 pts). Miami's -37 round torched all the ground gained in China and Japan in a single afternoon, and until Hulkenberg stops self-destructing the bottom two is your home." } };
